  --max-tokens-per-gpu         1024
  --log-probs-chunk-size       128

Correctness debugging journey (why step 0 was off by ~0.28)
-----------------------------------------------------------

Initial symptom: first 30B-A3B run had train_rollout_logprob_abs_diff ~0.285
across every step, ~14x the 0.02 bar, while Nano-4B dense passed cleanly.

Things that were NOT the cause (ruled out, all left no effect on the diff):

  --moe-router-num-groups 8 --moe-router-group-topk 1
  --moe-router-topk-scaling-factor 2.5 --moe-router-pre-softmax (via CLI)
  --moe-router-load-balancing-type none + --moe-aux-loss-coeff 0
  --moe-router-load-balancing-type seq_aux_loss + bias-update-rate 0
  router expert_bias load (verified via one-shot diag print,
    abs.max=56.789, matches HF's ~57-magnitude aux-free balance bias)
  hybrid_override_pattern replay alignment (moe_layer_freq mirror into
    provider so replay_utils registers once per real MoE layer)

Root cause:

  miles' generic model_provider.py only copies a small subset of moe_* CLI
  args to the Megatron provider after AutoBridge.to_megatron_provider().
  The critical moe_router_topk_scaling_factor (=2.5 for Nemotron-H) was
  never propagated, so Megatron's forward scaled routed-expert output by
  1.0 instead of 2.5. Compounded across 22 MoE layers this was a ~500x
  probability miscalibration per token even with bit-exact loaded weights.

Fix:

  In the NemotronHBridge provider shim (miles/backends/megatron_utils/
  __init__.py), pull routed_scaling_factor, n_group, topk_group straight
  out of the HF config and force moe_router_dtype=fp32.

Validation (scripts/tools/debug_nemotron_moe_weight_check.py, single-rank):

  before shim:  Megatron vs HF per-token logprob mean=2.08  max=6.21
  after  shim:  Megatron vs HF per-token logprob mean=0.006 max=0.022
                (matches Nano-4B dense's 0.01 band)
